raw": "The Great War", "machine_tag": 0, "id": "14435201-4700405902-921322", "_content": "thegreatwar", "author": "14456531@N07"}, {"raw": "First World War", "machine_tag": 0, "id": "14435201-4700405902-49776", "_content": "firstworldwar", "author": "14456531@N07"}, {"raw": "World War I", "machine_tag": 0, "id": "14435201-4700405902-13083", "_content": "worldwari", "author": "14456531@N07"}, {"raw": "sand bags", "machine_tag": 0, "id": "14435201-4700405902-99439", "_content": "sandbags", "author": "14456531@N07"}, {"raw": "tpc", "machine_tag": 0, "id": "14435201-4700405902-114399", "_content": "tpc", "author": "45516516@N07"}, {"raw": "tpcu13", "machine_tag": 0, "id": "14435201-4700405902-64820427", "_content": "tpcu13", "author": "45516516@N07"}, {"raw": "tpcu13l2", "machine_tag": 0, "id": "14435201-4700405902-64895288", "_content": "tpcu13l2", "author": "45516516@N07"}]}, "comments": {"_content": "0"}, "secret": "a8ff99d848", "usage": {"canblog": 0, "canshare": 1, "candownload": 1, "canprint": 0}, "description": {"_content": "As this photograph shows, it was not only submarines that needed periscopes during World War I. This ingenious method of keeping watch on the enemys movements was certainly much safer than putting ones head above the trench parapet. A less sophisticated form of trench periscope was a small mirror attached to the tip of a bayonet on a rifle. \n\nWorld War I was infamous for the massive number of head wounds that were suffered during the conflict, so periscopes increasingly played a large part in sentry duty. Since this could only work during daylight hours, however, the most likely time for an attack was at dawn or dusk. During the day, sentries were placed at regular intervals along the trench, and they would have the vital duty of using the periscope to watch for any threatening movements by the enemy.\n\n[Original reads: 'OFFICIAL PHOTOGRAPHS TAKEN ON THE FRONT IN FRANCE. Watching the Boche trench through a periscope.']\n\n<a href=\"http://